    "instruction": "Load the four CSV files (metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, error_logs.csv). For each file, return a compact summary only: (1) total row count, (2) minimum and maximum timestamp, (3) list of distinct cmdb_id values (limit to top 50), and (4) list of distinct KPI/trace/log names (kpi_name for metric.csv, trace_name for trace.csv, log_name for log.csv) (limit each list to top 50). Additionally, for error_logs.csv return the first 20 rows (all columns) as sample rows. Do not print full raw tables beyond these summaries."
}

{
    "analysis": "The telemetry files were successfully loaded. Key findings from the summary: metric.csv contains 326,396 rows spanning 2022-03-21 19:30:00 to 2022-03-21 20:30:00 (Asia/Shanghai); trace.csv and log.csv cover the incident window 20:00–20:30; error_logs.csv contains 14 rows concentrated at 20:00:00–20:01:28 (Asia/Shanghai). The error logs show many frontend-* \"request error\" entries and one shippingservice-1 entry at timestamp 1647864024 (~2022-03-21 20:00:24 CST+0800) with a 503 upstream error — this indicates an early error burst around 20:00:00–20:01:30 involving frontend pods and shippingservice-1. To localize root cause we should next inspect metric KPI names related to resources (CPU, memory, network, IO, latency, counts, errors) so we can compute global thresholds for candidate KPIs and then detect anomalies within the incident window. The next step is to enumerate relevant KPI names from metric.csv (case-insensitive keyword match) and provide compact stats per KPI so we can choose which KPIs to analyze further.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv, find distinct kpi_name values that match (case-insensitive) any of these keywords: cpu, memory, mem, heap, gc, thread, net, packet, io, disk, read, write, latency, duration, error, count, success, throughput, req, rt, time. For each matching kpi_name, return a compact row with: kpi_name, total row count (rows), number of distinct cmdb_id that have this kpi, min_timestamp, max_timestamp. Order results by row count descending and limit to top 200 rows. Keep output terse (columns only)."
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous step loaded the four CSVs and produced a keyword-filtered list of metric kpi_names. Key observations: metric.csv covers 19:30–20:30 and contains many network- and mesh-related metrics (e.g., container network receive/transmit, network error counts, and many istio mesh request/response metrics). trace.csv and log.csv cover the incident window (20:00–20:30). error_logs.csv has 14 rows concentrated at 20:00:00–20:01:28 (Asia/Shanghai) showing repeated \"request error\" entries from frontend-* pods and a shippingservice-1 entry at timestamp 1647864024 (~2022-03-21 20:00:24 CST+0800) reporting a 503 upstream error. This suggests the failure began around 20:00:00 and involved frontend pods making requests that saw upstream 503s from shippingservice-1 or its upstream.\n\nWhat to do next: follow the workflow (preprocess -> anomaly detection -> fault identification -> localization). We should narrow metric analysis to the components implicated by logs first (frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, and shippingservice-1). To prepare for global-threshold calculation per 'component-KPI', we need to know which KPI names exist for these components (CPU, memory, network errors, istio request rates/latencies, etc.). I will therefore request a compact inventory of KPI names for those candidate components so we can choose which KPIs to compute thresholds on.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv, filter rows where cmdb_id is one of: frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, shippingservice-1. Group by cmdb_id and kpi_name and return a compact table with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, rows (count), min_timestamp, max_timestamp. Order by rows descending and limit to top 200 rows. Keep output terse (no full raw series). Also return the count of distinct kpi_name values found for each cmdb_id (one additional small table or appended column)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have loaded telemetry and narrowed candidates from logs to frontend-0/1/2 and shippingservice-1. Metrics show many network/container and istio/mesh KPIs for these components. Error logs concentrate at 2022-03-21 20:00:00–20:01:28 (Asia/Shanghai) with repeated frontend \"request error\" entries and a shippingservice-1 503 upstream at ~20:00:24. Next we must calculate global thresholds on the most relevant KPIs for these candidate components (network, container CPU/memory, istio request/response counts and latencies, and any error counters) before filtering to the incident window. To choose KPI time series for threshold calculation, we need a compact inventory of the most frequent KPIs for each candidate component and a focused list of KPIs that likely indicate network/HTTP upstream failures (keywords such as istio, req, resp, upstream, receive, transmit, error, cpu, mem, io, disk).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv, for cmdb_id in [frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, shippingservice-1] do two compact outputs: (A) For each cmdb_id, list the top 20 kpi_name by row count with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, rows, min_timestamp, max_timestamp (order by cmdb_id then rows desc). (B) For the same cmdb_ids, return all distinct kpi_name that match (case-insensitive) any of these substrings: 'istio','req','resp','upstream','receive','transmit','error','cpu','mem','memory','io','disk','latency','duration'. For each matching kpi_name provide: cmdb_id, kpi_name, rows. Limit output rows to at most 200. Keep outputs terse (only specified columns)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have narrowed candidates to frontend-0/1/2 and shippingservice-1 based on error_logs and KPI inventory. The metrics show many istio/mesh request metrics and container network/error metrics for these components. The next required step (per rules) is to compute global thresholds for relevant component-KPI time series using the full available series (not filtered to incident window). By comparing P95 (and P5) across these component-KPI series we can find KPIs that show extreme deviations during the incident window and then filter to 20:00–20:30 to locate consecutive anomalies. Thus we must compute global P95 and P5 for each candidate component-KPI for KPIs that are likely to indicate upstream/HTTP/network issues (istio, upstream, receive/transmit, error, packet, request/resp/status, network, cpu, mem).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, select rows where cmdb_id is one of: frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, shippingservice-1 and kpi_name (case-insensitive) contains any of these substrings: 'istio','upstream','receive','transmit','error','packet','request','resp','code','status','network','cpu','mem','memory'. For each group (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: rows (count), min_timestamp, max_timestamp, P95 of value, and P5 of value. Ensure 'value' is numeric when computing percentiles. Return a compact table with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, rows, min_timestamp, max_timestamp, p95_value, p5_value. Order the output by cmdb_id then by p95_value descending and limit to top 200 rows. Keep output terse (only the specified columns)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We computed global P95 and P5 for many (cmdb_id, kpi_name) groups for the four candidate components (frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, shippingservice-1). The results show per-minute series across 61 minutes (1647862200–1647865800, i.e., 2022-03-21 19:30:00 to 20:30:00 CST+0800). Error logs concentrate at ~20:00:00–20:01:30 and implicate frontend pods and shippingservice-1 (a 503 upstream at ~1647864024). Next we must perform anomaly detection within the incident window (20:00–20:30) using the previously computed global thresholds (p95/p5) per (cmdb_id,kpi_name). We should identify which component-KPI series show consecutive anomalies in that window and surface the earliest anomaly timestamps and severity metrics so we can prioritize faults for trace/log correlation.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv and the previously computed table of (cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95_value, p5_value) stored in result_df, detect anomalies inside the incident window 2022-03-21 20:00:00 to 2022-03-21 20:30:00 Asia/Shanghai (Executor will handle timestamp conversion). For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) present in result_df do the following:\n1) Load the metric time series for that group for the full incident window.\n2) Mark a point as anomalous if value >= p95_value OR value <= p5_value.\n3) Aggregate consecutive anomalous points into fault segments. For each group, compute: number of anomalous points (anomaly_point_count), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (first anomalous point in window), latest_anomaly_timestamp (last anomalous point in window), max_value, min_value within the window, and include p95_value and p5_value for reference.\nReturn a compact table with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_point_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, latest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value, min_value, p95_value, p5_value. Order results by anomaly_point_count descending then by absolute deviation (max(|max_value/p95_value -1|, |min_value/p5_value -1|)) descending. Limit output to top 20 rows. Keep output terse (only the specified columns)."
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous step ran anomaly detection on selected metric groups for frontend-0/1/2 and shippingservice-1 using global P95/P5 thresholds and then filtered out constant/config-like KPIs. That filtering removed all candidate anomalies, so metric-based signals did not yield clear, non-trivial faults for the candidate components. Meanwhile, error_logs.csv already showed an early error burst at ~1647864000–1647864088 (2022-03-21 20:00:00–20:01:28 CST+0800) with repeated \"request error\" entries from frontend-* pods and a shippingservice-1 503 upstream entry at 1647864024 (~20:00:24). Given metrics produced many false positives (constant series), the next logical step is to use traces (which capture inter-service latencies and error rates) to localize which service calls were faulty during the incident window. Traces often reveal downstream failed services or increased durations even when some metrics are constant. Therefore we should compute global thresholds for trace features (per cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full trace.csv series and then detect anomalies inside the incident window (2022-03-21 20:00:00 to 20:30:00 CST+0800). We'll request a compact ranked list of trace groups that show the most anomalous behavior in the incident window (anomaly count and earliest anomaly time), including their global p95/p5 and window min/max to prioritize candidates for log correlation.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From trace.csv, for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) group compute global P95 and P5 of 'value' using the full available series. Then, for the incident window 2022-03-21 20:00:00 to 2022-03-21 20:30:00 Asia/Shanghai, load that group's values and mark points anomalous if value >= P95 OR value <= P5. Aggregate anomalies per group and return the top 20 groups ordered by anomaly_point_count descending then by earliest_anomaly_timestamp ascending. Return columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, rows_total (full-series count), rows_in_window (count in incident window), anomaly_point_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, latest_anomaly_timestamp, p95_value, p5_value, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window. Keep output limited to top 20 rows and terse (only specified columns)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We exhausted metric- and trace-based threshold anomalies but most flagged series were constant/config values (p95==p5==observed) producing false positives. The error_logs.csv already shows a tight error burst at 2022-03-21 20:00:00–20:01:28 (Asia/Shanghai) with repeated \"request error\" entries from frontend-0/1/2 and one shippingservice-1 message at epoch 1647864024 indicating a 503 upstream. Trace groups we inspected were zero-only and not informative. Therefore logs are the most promising source now to localize the root cause component and exact occurrence time: we should (1) quantify error log volume per component in the incident window, (2) sample messages to identify upstream HTTP error codes or upstream service names, and (3) check normalized log metrics (log.error_count, log.row_count) per component during the window to confirm which components experienced elevated error counts and when the first error occurred. This will let us pick candidate root-cause components/timestamps for final correlation with traces/metrics.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From error_logs.csv and log.csv, restrict to the incident window 2022-03-21 20:00:00 to 2022-03-21 20:30:00 Asia/Shanghai (Executor will handle timestamp conversion). Produce two compact outputs:\n\n1) error_logs.csv aggregation: For each cmdb_id present in error_logs within the window, return: cmdb_id, total_error_rows (count), earliest_error_timestamp, latest_error_timestamp, and up to 5 distinct sample message texts (short). Order rows by total_error_rows descending and limit to top 20 cmdb_ids.\n\n2) log.csv aggregation: For each cmdb_id present in log.csv within the window, compute sum_error_count = sum(value) for rows where log_name == 'log.error_count', and sum_row_count = sum(value) for rows where log_name == 'log.row_count'. Also return earliest_timestamp where log.error_count > 0 (if any) for that cmdb_id (return null if none). Return columns: cmdb_id, sum_error_count, sum_row_count, earliest_error_count_timestamp. Order by sum_error_count descending and limit to top 20 rows. Keep outputs terse (only specified columns and message samples)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have progressed through preprocessing and thresholding. Metrics and trace-thresholding flagged many constant/config series (p95==p5==observed) which created false positives, so metric-based localization was inconclusive. Error logs are the most informative source so far: error_logs.csv shows a concentrated burst at 2022-03-21 20:00:00–20:01:28 (Asia/Shanghai) with repeated \"request error\" entries from frontend-0/1/2 and a shippingservice-1 log at 1647864024 (≈2022-03-21 20:00:24) reporting a 503 upstream. log.csv aggregates confirm frontend pods saw elevated log.error_count at 20:00:00. Given these facts, the most promising next step is targeted trace analysis: inspect trace.csv during the incident window for traces originating from frontends (trace_name containing 'from_frontend') and any traces for shippingservice-1 (or trace names mentioning 'shipping') to find non-zero error_rates or duration spikes that correlate with the log errors. If traces show that calls from frontend->shippingservice experienced 503/error or large latency starting at ~20:00:24, shippingservice-1 is likely the root cause; otherwise frontends may be misconfigured or downstream networks/nodes might be at fault.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From trace.csv, restrict to the incident window 2022-03-21 20:00:00 to 2022-03-21 20:30:00 Asia/Shanghai (Executor will handle timestamp conversion). Filter rows where either: trace_name contains 'from_frontend' (case-insensitive) OR cmdb_id == 'shippingservice-1' OR trace_name contains 'shipping' (case-insensitive). Group by cmdb_id and trace_name and compute: rows_in_window (count), anomaly_count = count of points with value > 0, earliest_nonzero_timestamp (first timestamp with value>0 in window, null if none), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window. Order results by anomaly_count descending then max_value_in_window descending and limit to top 20 rows. Return only the specified columns (cmdb_id, trace_name, rows_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_nonzero_timestamp, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We inspected metrics and traces broadly but found many constant/config series that produced false-positive threshold breaches, so metric-based localization was inconclusive. Error logs are the most actionable signal: error_logs.csv shows a concentrated burst at 2022-03-21 20:00:00–20:01:28 (Asia/Shanghai) with repeated \"severity: error, message: request error\" from frontend-1/0/2 and a shippingservice-1 entry at 1647864024 (~2022-03-21 20:00:24) that contains a \"POST ... 503\" upstream message. log.csv confirms elevated log.error_count for frontend-0/1/2 at 20:00:00. Trace aggregation across many services shows steady request volumes (trace.from_frontend-*.row_count) but did not reveal obvious non-zero error metrics using the simple P95/P5 rule (many trace metrics are zero-only). Given the log evidence (frontends saw immediate request errors and shippingservice-1 logged a 503 at ~20:00:24), the next concrete step is targeted trace analysis of call paths between the frontend pods and shippingservice (and shippingservice-1 specifically) using proper global thresholds (P95/P5 computed from the full trace series) and then detecting anomalies in the incident window. This will confirm whether frontend errors were caused by shippingservice-1 (e.g., upstream 503s or latency spikes) or whether the frontends themselves or the network were the root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From trace.csv compute global P95 and P5 per (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full available series. Restrict attention to groups where (a) cmdb_id is one of [frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, shippingservice-1] OR (b) trace_name contains the substring 'shipping' OR 'from_frontend' (case-insensitive). Then, for the incident window 2022-03-21 20:00:00 to 2022-03-21 20:30:00 Asia/Shanghai (Executor will convert), load each group's points in that window and mark anomalies where value >= P95 OR value <= P5. For each group return a compact row with: cmdb_id, trace_name, rows_total (full-series count), rows_in_window, anomaly_point_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (in window, null if none), latest_anomaly_timestamp (in window), p95_value, p5_value, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window. Order results by anomaly_point_count desc then earliest_anomaly_timestamp asc and limit to top 20 rows. Keep output terse (only the specified columns)."
}

